The first goal was accomplished when Caesar defeated Pompey and his supporters.[91] To accomplish the other two goals, he needed to ensure that his control over the government was undisputed,[92] so he assumed these powers by increasing his own authority, and by decreasing the authority of Rome's other political institutions. Finally, he enacted a series of reforms that were meant to address several long-neglected issues, the most important of which was his reform of the calendar.[93]
